[351.802081, "o", "grep -nE \"POST|PUT|DELETE|/api/notes|X-API-Key|X-Total-Count|limit|offset|OPTIONS|error|NOTES_MAX_BODY_BYTES\" /app/docs/api_contract.md | head -n 200\r\n"]
[351.802254, "o", "\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[351.804867, "o", "3:Store notes in /app/data/notes.db. Read the shared secret from /app/config/api.key and trim surrounding whitespace before comparing it to the X-API-Key header on mutating requests. The stock api.key file ships with tb3_notes_api_secret_2026. POST, PUT, and DELETE require a matching key or the server responds unauthorized. GET never requires the key; a bad or missing key on a mutating call is unauthorized.\r\n5:Every JSON response must use a JSON content type and include an access-control header that allows any origin. OPTIONS preflight must advertise GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, and OPTIONS, and must allow Content-Type and X-API-Key as request headers. Preflight may return empty or non-empty success.\r\n7:POST /api/notes accepts JSON with string title and content. Title must be present and non-empty; an empty object or missing or blank title is a client error. Success is HTTP 201 with a body containing numeric id plus stored title and content. GET /api/notes returns a JSON array of objects with id, title, and content. Optional limit and offset query parameters are integers: default limit 50, maximum 100, default offset 0. /api/notes?limit=100 returns at most one hundred rows; /api/notes?limit=999 is capped the same way. The total row count before paging goes in the X-Total-Count header.\r\n9:GET /api/notes/{id} returns that object. A missing id returns HTTP 404 with JSON {\"error\":\"not found\"} using that exact lowercase message string, including for ids such as /api/notes/99999 on GET, PUT, or DELETE. PUT uses the same field rules as POST, returns HTTP 200 with saved fields when the row exists, or the same not-found JSON when it does not. Successful DELETE returns HTTP 200 with JSON {\"status\":\"deleted\"}; deleting a missing id returns the same not-found JSON as GET. Reject POST or PUT bodies larger than 65536 bytes with HTTP 413 and a JSON error body.\r\n11:SQLite access must remain correct under concurrent requests. Verifiers may reset /app/data/notes.db and send bursts of about fifteen parallel POST requests; every stored row m"]
[351.804999, "o", "ust still appear in responses afterward.\r\n"]
[351.80524, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[351.805368, "o", "root@bb40ba43d60f:/app# "]
[351.920955, "i", "grep -nE \"status|HTTP|201|204|400|401|404|413|415|422|429|500|Access-Control|Content-Type\" /app/docs/api_contract.md | head -n 200\n"]
[351.922004, "o", "grep -nE \"status|HTTP|201|204|400|401|404|413|415|422|429|500|Access-Control|Content-Type\" /app/docs/api_contract.md | head -n 200\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[351.925365, "o", "1:This document is the normative REST contract for the notes API. Automated checks use arbitrary title and content strings in requests; only the behaviors, status codes, headers, and JSON field names here matter.\r\n5:Every JSON response must use a JSON content type and include an access-control header that allows any origin. OPTIONS preflight must advertise GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, and OPTIONS, and must allow Content-Type and X-API-Key as request headers. Preflight may return empty or non-empty success.\r\n7:POST /api/notes accepts JSON with string title and content. Title must be present and non-empty; an empty object or missing or blank title is a client error. Success is HTTP 201 with a body containing numeric id plus stored title and content. GET /api/notes returns a JSON array of objects with id, title, and content. Optional limit and offset query parameters are integers: default limit 50, maximum 100, default offset 0. /api/notes?limit=100 returns at most one hundred rows; /api/notes?limit=999 is capped the same way. The total row count before paging goes in the X-Total-Count header.\r\n9:GET /api/notes/{id} returns that object. A missing id returns HTTP 404 with JSON {\"error\":\"not found\"} using that exact lowercase message string, including for ids such as /api/notes/99999 on GET, PUT, or DELETE. PUT uses the same field rules as POST, returns HTTP 200 with saved fields when the row exists, or the same not-found JSON when it does not. Successful DELETE returns HTTP 200 with JSON {\"status\":\"deleted\"}; deleting a missing id returns the same not-found JSON as GET. Reject POST or PUT bodies larger than 65536 bytes with HTTP 413 and a JSON error body.\r\n"]
[351.926375, "o", "\u001b[?2004hroot@bb40ba43d60f:/app# "]
